{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488403"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:40:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"432"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/432"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.05,0.09,0.04,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90571"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74782"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"396"},{"type":"tags","id":"1008"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2142"},{"type":"tags","id":"2494"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30229"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31080"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90571"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of coughing up small quantities of fresh blood. He has also experienced pleuritic chest pain and increasing breathlessness. He feels generally unwell and feverish. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 124/64 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is reduced air entry bilaterally with dull percussion notes at both lung bases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 120 g/L (115-155)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 200 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 10.0 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.0-10.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECreatinine 150 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESodium 135 mmol/L (137-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPotassium 4.5 mmol/L (3.5-4.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows blood ++, no protein, no leucocytes, no nitrates. Red cell casts are present on urinary sediment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most definitive diagnostic test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["ANCA levels","Chest X-ray","CT Pulmonary Angiogram","Pleural tap","Renal biopsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture - together with the laboratory results - show evidence of a pulmonary and renal problem, both suggesting anti-glomerular basement membrane (anti-GBM) disease; also known as Goodpasture syndrome. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-GBM disease is a rare small vessel vasculitis that affects the capillary beds of the kidneys and lungs. It is an autoimmune condition that is caused by development of autoantibodies against autoantigen expressed in the basement membranes of these organs although the full pathogenesis is not fully understood. Most patients develop widespread glomerular crescent formation, presenting with features of rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis and about 40%\u201360% will have concurrent alveolar haemorrhage. Red cell casts are highly abnormal and point towards glomerular bleeding. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other possible unifying diagnoses for his haemoptysis and glomerulonephritis (often termed \u0027pulmonary-renal syndrome\u0027) are vasculitis due to granulomatosis with polyangiitis, lupus, and microscopic polyangiitis; all of which could potentially be diagnosed with the renal biopsy. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERenal biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the definitive diagnostic test for anti-GBM disease. It allows direct visualization of glomerular damage and, most importantly, immunofluorescence studies can demonstrate the linear deposition of IgG antibodies along the glomerular basement membrane, which is pathognomonic for the condition. Renal biopsy can also help diagnose other causes of pulmonary-renal syndrome such as ANCA-associated vasculitis or lupus nephritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EANCA levels\u003C/strong\u003E would be helpful in diagnosing ANCA-associated vasculitides such as granulomatosis with polyangiitis (formerly Wegener\u0027s granulomatosis) or microscopic polyangiitis, which can also present with pulmonary-renal syndrome. However, anti-GBM disease can sometimes exist in the absence of circulating antibodies, and approximately 30% of patients with anti-GBM disease are also ANCA positive, making this test less definitive than renal biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E may show bilateral alveolar infiltrates in pulmonary haemorrhage but is non-specific and cannot differentiate between the various causes of pulmonary-renal syndrome. It may be useful as an initial investigation but is not definitive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT Pulmonary Angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be useful to exclude pulmonary embolism, which can present with pleuritic chest pain and haemoptysis. However, it would not explain the urinary findings and would not be diagnostic for anti-GBM disease or other vasculitides.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural tap\u003C/strong\u003E would not be diagnostic in this case as the primary pathology is alveolar haemorrhage rather than pleural effusion. Even if pleural fluid were present, analysis would not provide a definitive diagnosis for the underlying condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-GBM disease is a rare autoimmune condition where antibodies target antigens in the basement membranes of the lungs and kidneys. It typically presents with rapidly progressive glomerulonephritis and pulmonary haemorrhage. Early diagnosis and treatment with plasma exchange, corticosteroids, and cyclophosphamide are crucial to prevent irreversible kidney damage and life-threatening pulmonary haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anti-glomerular basement membrane disease (Goodpasture syndrome) presents with pulmonary haemorrhage and glomerulonephritis.","Red cell casts in urine are highly suggestive of glomerular bleeding.","Renal biopsy with immunofluorescence is the definitive diagnostic test for anti-GBM disease."],"references":["McCabe, C., Jones, Q., Nikolopoulou, A., Wathen, C. and Luqmani, R., 2011. Pulmonary-renal syndromes: An update for respiratory physicians. Respiratory Medicine, 105(10), pp.1413-1421.","Nath A, Rajagopala S. Pulmonary renal syndromes: A pulmonologist\u0027s view. Clinical Queries: Nephrology. 2015;4(1-2):1-8.","McAdoo S, Pusey C. Anti-Glomerular Basement Membrane Disease. Clinical Journal of the American Society of Nephrology. 2017;12(7):1162-1172."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74782"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"432"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions",